%N A396941 Decimal expansion of the probability that an acute triangle is formed by selecting two points independently and uniformly at random on a fixed radius of a disk, and a third point independently and uniformly at random in the disk.
%C A396941 The solution to Problem 3258 (1871) has an error: (y-x)^2*Pi in eq. (1), representing the area of the small circle in the plot, should be ((y-x)/2)^2*Pi. As a consequence, the value 4/(3*Pi) - 5/12 given in the solution is incorrect.
%H A396941 Artemas Martin, <a href="https://archive.org/details/mathematicalque19millgoog/page/n101/mode/1up">Problem 3258</a>, with a solution by Stephen Watson, Mathematical Questions with Their Solutions, from the "Educational Times", Vol. 14, (1871), p. 97.
%H A396941 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
%F A396941 Equals 4/(3*Pi) - 7/24.
%e A396941 0.1327465149117208953836900356600382987585590553078838...
%t A396941 RealDigits[4/(3*Pi) - 7/24, 10, 120][[1]]
